The apodosis to the whole sentence is the original ‘Quid leges proficiunt Ῥ ‘ Horrida . . navitae ’ and ‘ magnum . . arduae ' are both constructed after ‘si.' The asyndeton serves to point out that the last two clauses are not fresh instances of that general thirst for wealth which belies sumptumylaws, but two explanations of the merchant's boldness: if the sea is rough the seaman is cunning (for the relation of the two adjectives see on 1. 3. 10) to overcome its difficulties, and in any case there is the prevailing motive behind, the dread of the one great shame, poverty.
